'''''Air Raid''''' is a 1982 [[shoot 'em up]] published for the [[Atari 2600]] by [[Men-A-Vision]], the only game released by the company.<ref name="Weiss2011">{{cite book|last=Weiss|first=Brett|title=Classic Home Video Games, 1972â€“1984: A Complete Reference Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BzxTtml8Jq4C&pg=PA30|date=4 April 2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8755-4|page=30}}</ref> The cartridge is a blue T-handle design with a picture of flying saucers attacking a futuristic city.  It had extremely limited distribution,<ref name="AirRaidPolygon">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2012/10/25/3555866/the-atari-2600-air-raid-cartridge-a-story-of-serendipity |date=25 October 2012 |title=Family unearths rare Atari game from storage, it could sell for $30,000 |last=Corriea |first=Alexa Ray |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> making it highly sought after by [[Video game collecting|video game collectors]].

==Gameplay==
The player controls a ship which scrolls side-to side directly above two buildings, with the objective of protecting the buildings from being destroyed by the bombs of enemy ships above.<ref name="Weiss2011"/>

==Rarity==
[[File:airraidmenavision.png|thumb|left]]
On April 10, 2010, the only copy at the time known to be complete (cartridge and box) sold for $31,600.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toplessrobot.com/2010/04/man_pays_31600_for_an_atari_game_--_seriously.php |date=2010-04-13 |title=Man Pays $31,600 for an Atari Game - Seriously |last=Bricken |first=Rob |website=Topless Robot |publisher=Voice Media Group |accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref> The next known copy to surface on the internet was on October 22, 2011. The [[eBay]] auction offered an incomplete version of the game (cart only). ''Air Raid'' still sold for an impressive amount of $3,575 US. The transaction was completed, having both parties exchange positive feedback making this the second highest confirmed price paid for the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogameauctions.com/air-raid-atari-2600-sells-for-3575/ |title=Air Raid Atari 2600 Sells for $3,575 |publisher=VideoGameAuctions.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113030147/http://www.videogameauctions.com/air-raid-atari-2600-sells-for-3575/ |archive-date=2011-11-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On October 24, 2012, the first truly complete game (cartridge, instruction manual and box) was listed for auction and eventually sold for $33,433.30.<ref name="AirRaidPolygon"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamegavel.com/item.cgi?show_item=0000687017 |date=4 November 2012 |title=The ONE THE ONLY Complete Air Raid Ever Found - CIB |last=Bennett |first=Harv |website=GameGavel  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108220543/http://www.gamegavel.com/item.cgi?show_item=0000687017 |archive-date=8 November 2012}}</ref> Due to the media attention that this complete copy brought, on October 26, 2012, a third boxed copy (although without the instruction manual) surfaced on eBay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebay.com/itm/ws/eBayISAPI.dll?ViewItem&item=281011192303 |title=Atari 2600 Air Raid Game in Original Box Extremely RARE |publisher=eBay |date= |accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref> On June 28, 2021, a [[Goodwill Industries|Goodwill]] employee in [[Fort Worth, Texas]] found and auctioned off a playable copy of the game at eBay for $10,590.79, which was a success for the company to raise more than $10,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.star-telegram.com/news/local/fort-worth/article252421983.html|date=2021-06-28|title=Rare Atari game donated to Fort Worth Goodwill store sold to bidder for record amount|last=Stevenson|first=Stefan|website=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|publisher=[[McClatchy]]|accessdate=2021-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/arts-entertainment/pop-culture/2021/06/28/rare-atari-game-found-at-a-fort-worth-goodwill-nets-more-than-10k-at-auction/|date=2021-06-28|title=Rare Atari game found at a Fort Worth Goodwill nets more than $10K at auction|last=Caplan|first=Anna|website=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|publisher=[[A. H. Belo]]|accessdate=2021-06-30}}</ref>

